There's a Bulgarian folk story about an old hunter who chases after a hare all day trying to catch it until finally cornered at dusk it jumps into a river and drowns. Nightfall finds him far from home so he goes to a nearby village and knocks on the richest house asking to stay.

Not the point of the tale but it always fascinated me how back in the day you could supposedly just get sorta lost somewhere in the country and ask a random household to let you eat and sleep with them for a night and they'd be happy to house you. Very romantic image in the mind.

When men say they want a woman to "ruin their life", what they mean is they want to go through various violent hardships and adversities together, peril being the crucible of romantic love. What is ruined here is the outer, "bourgeois" (normie), external layer of one's existence.

Just as a deep love has this potential catastrophic effect on one's standing in civil society, etc. so it can be catastrophic on the more "conditioned" aspects of the romantic relation itself, manifesting in apparent disdain between lovers or hatred for each other (Mart winning).

What one means to say is that no one desires destruction as such, but merely a love so potent that it can produce it. As rheumatism in the hands of an old soldier proves him having camped in the snow during wartime. So scars, wounds serve as metonymy for that which produces them.
